\ls1\ilvl1\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f2 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 By selecting "Display," you offload the scaling task to your monitor\'92s internal hardware. While modern GPUs (like your RTX 5070) are extremely fast, using the display's scaler is the traditional "path of least resistance" for the signal.\uc0\u8232 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1
\f3\i \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f2\i0 \uc0\u9702 
\f3\i 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Note:
\f0\i0  If you notice significant blurring or lag when running non-native resolutions, switch this to 
\f1\b GPU
\f0\b0 , as your 5070's scaler is likely superior to many older monitor scalers.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
