\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 Hardware Context\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 While the settings above are the general "performance" standard, knowing your specific hardware helps for these reasons:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 RTX 5070 Performance:
\f0\b0  Since you have a high-end modern GPU, the "cost" of GPU scaling is virtually zero (less than 1ms). If you play competitive sims like 
\f1\b iRacing
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b ACC
\f0\b0  and prefer "Stretched" views (4:3 on a 16:9 screen), you 
\f3\i must
\f0\i0  set this to 
\f1\b GPU
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b Full-screen
\f0\b0  to force the stretch.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Monitor Scaler Quality:
\f0\b0  If your Dell or gaming monitor is a high-refresh-rate "G-Sync Compatible" model, its internal scaler is likely very fast. However, if you are using an older display (like your wife's older laptop or a budget secondary screen), the monitor's scaler might add 5-10ms of lag, in which case 
\f1\b GPU scaling
\f0\b0  would actually be faster.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Sim Racing Specifics:
\f0\b0  For 
\f1\b Assetto Corsa
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b Le Mans Ultimate
\f0\b0 , running at your monitor's 
\f1\b Native Resolution
\f0\b0  is the single best thing you can do for performance. Scaling should only be a "backup" if your GPU is struggling to maintain your target FPS.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

