\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 Is the AMD Chipset Software Necessary?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 Yes.
\f0\b0  Unlike the SDK, you should keep the Chipset Software installed. It includes several low-level drivers that are vital for a high-performance gaming PC:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AMD Ryzen PPV (Provisioning Package):
\f0\b0  Helps Windows understand the power capabilities of your specific CPU.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AMD MicroPEP Driver:
\f0\b0  Manages power transitions (sleeping/waking) more efficiently than the generic Windows driver.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AMD PCI Device Driver:
\f0\b0  Essential for the high-speed communication between your CPU, GPU, and NVMe SSD.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AMD GPIO Driver:
\f0\b0  Manages the general-purpose pins on the processor that talk to various motherboard components.\uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 The "Software Minimization" Strategy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 Since your goal is a lean system, here is how to handle these:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Ditch MSI Center:
\f0\b0  If you only used it to install drivers, you can safely uninstall the entire MSI Center suite. It is heavy, uses multiple background services, and often triggers telemetry.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Standalone Chipset Drivers:
\f0\b0  Instead of letting MSI manage them, download the 
\f1\b standalone
\f0\b0  installer directly from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amd.com/en/support"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 AMD's Support Page}}.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f2 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 This gives you the drivers without the MSI "bloatware" wrapper.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The "Clean" Install:
