\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 Hardware-Specific Advice for LMU & OBS\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The X3D Factor:
\f0\b0  Since \cf5 \cb6 \strokec5 amd3dvcacheSvc\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  was stopped in your log, reinstall the 
\f1\b AMD Chipset Drivers
\f0\b0  (Version 6.x or newer) and ensure 
\f1\b Windows Game Mode
\f0\b0  is 
\f1\b ON
\f0\b0 . This is the trigger that tells the 9850X3D to prioritize the V-Cache CCD for LMU.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 iCue "Hardware Mode":
\f0\b0  In iCue, configure your fan curves and RGB, then save them to the 
\f1\b "Device Memory"
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b "Hardware Lighting."
\f0\b0  You can then set all Corsair services to 
\f1\b Manual
\f0\b0  and close iCue entirely before launching LMU to prevent the known "Corsair CPU polling" stutters.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 OBS Encoding:
\f0\b0  Use 
\f1\b NVENC AV1
\f0\b0  (since you have a 50-series card). This uses a dedicated chip on the GPU that has zero impact on your LMU frame rates or CPU physics calculations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

