\cf2 \strokec2 Would you like the specific steps to enable the "Advanced" view in the NVIDIA App to see your GPU power and temperatures?\
\
Which would have less impact on performance?\
\
The **NVIDIA App overlay** generally has less impact on performance than the Steam Performance Monitor, primarily because of how it accesses your hardware data.\
\
### 1. NVIDIA App (Lowest Impact)\
Since you are using an NVIDIA GPU, this tool is the most "efficient" because it talks directly to the driver.\
* **How it works:** It uses hardware-level polling. The "Advanced" overlay is essentially a lightweight wrapper for **NVIDIA FrameView**, which is designed to have a negligible impact (often <1%) on frame rates.\
* **Why it's better for you:** It is highly optimized for your RTX 5070. It uses specialized hardware paths to gather metrics like GPU power, clock speeds, and temperatures without waking up the CPU unnecessarily.\
\
### 2. Steam Performance Monitor (Slightly Higher Impact)\
While Valve significantly improved this in 2025, it still operates as a software-level injection layer.\
* **How it works:** It must "hook" into the game\'92s rendering pipeline to draw the graphs and text. \
* **Potential issues:** In the 2026 client, using the "Full Details" mode (with graphs and per-core CPU tracking) has been reported to cause minor stuttering or a 2\'963% FPS drop in CPU-bound scenarios. This is because it polls more frequently than the standard Windows Task Manager to provide "more accurate" data.\
* **Bug Note:** There are current reports of "NVIDIA Reflex + Boost" conflicting with the Steam overlay, sometimes causing incorrect GPU utilization readings or unexpected performance dips.\
\
---\
\
### Comparison at a Glance\
\
| Feature | NVIDIA App (`Alt + R`) | Steam Performance Monitor |\
| :--- | :--- | :--- |\
| **Performance Hit** | **Negligible (<1%)** | Low (2-3% in "Full" mode) |\
| **Stability** | Very High (Native Driver) | High (Software Injection) |\
| **Latency** | None (Hardware-based) | Minimal (Can add ~1-2ms) |\
| **Accuracy** | Best for GPU Power/Voltage | Best for RAM/CPU Per-Core |\
\
### Recommendation\
* **For competitive racing (iRacing, GT7 via Remote, etc.):** Use the **NVIDIA App (`Alt + R`)**. In high-stakes sim racing, you want the lowest possible input latency and zero stuttering from software hooks.\
* **For troubleshooting:** Only use the **Steam "Full Details"** overlay if you suspect a RAM leak or a specific CPU core is maxing out, then turn it back off once the issue is identified.\
\
**Would you like me to show you how to disable the "Game Filter" and "Photo Mode" inside the NVIDIA App?** These sub-features are the most common cause of actual performance loss within the NVIDIA overlay.\
